{
  "texts": [
    "According to a world-based view of possibilities, a \"possibility\" is simply a set of worlds; a possibility X \"refines\" a possibility Y iff X ⊆ Y; and however we define \"truth at a possibility,\" it should turn out that truth at a possibility is equivalent to truth at every world in that possibility (see Cresswell 2004 for this line of thinking, § 8.1 for other semantics that evaluate formulas at sets of worlds, and Humberstone 2019 for discussion of the \"flatness\" condition that truth at a set X of worlds is equivalent to truth at all singleton subsets of X).",
    "Thus, where ⊩ p is a proposed forcing relation between possibilities and formulas, and ⊨ w is the usual satisfaction relation between worlds and formulas (Definition A.2), it should hold that for all possibilities X and formulas φ: M, X ⊩ p φ iff ∀x ∈ X, M, {x} ⊩ p φ, where M, {x} ⊩ p φ iff M, x ⊨ w φ.",
    "(2.1) Fact 2.10 below records that the forcing relation ⊩ from Definition 2.3 is indeed such a ⊩ p satisfying (2.1).",
    "First, let us make official the construction of possibilities out of arbitrary sets of worlds.foot_11 Example 2.9 (Powerset Possibilization).",
    "Where F = ⟨W, {R i } i∈I, A⟩ is a world frame and M = ⟨F, V⟩ a world model, the powerset possibilizations of F and M, F ℘ = ⟨S, ⊑, {R i } i∈I, P ⟩ and M ℘ = ⟨F ℘, π⟩, are defined by:1."
  ]
}